article.description: Kevin Garnett scored a season-high 30 points and grabbed 19 rebounds, and the Minnesota Timberwolves overcame an impressive performance by Quentin Richardson to beat the Los Angeles Clippers 103-91 on Saturday night.
article.headline: KG racks up 30 points, 19 boards

images.name: Richardson Quentin 031122 275x200
images.caption: Clippers G Quentin Richardson eludes Minnesota's  Kevin Garnett in the first quarter.

article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Thirteen games into his Minnesota Timberwolves career, Sam Cassell is still getting used to playing with Kevin Garnett. It's tough for the NBA veteran, despite coach Flip Saunders' warning. "Sometimes you just get to watching him," Cassell said. "That's one thing Flip doesn't want us to do: Throw the ball to him and watch him. But Kevin's so good." Garnett scored a season-high 30 points and grabbed 19 rebounds, and the Timberwolves overcame an impressive performance by Quentin Richardson to beat the Los Angeles Clippers 103-91 on Saturday night. Richardson led the Clippers with a career-high 36 points on 12-for-19 shooting to keep Los Angeles within striking distance. But Garnett took over in the fourth quarter, grabbing rebounds, blocking shots and hitting baskets. "We were all talking about opening up the game," Garnett said. "We sensed they were a little tired. My mentality was to run, run, run, and see if they could run with us." They couldn't. He hit a 19-foot fadeaway as the shot clock expired to give the Wolves a 95-81 lead with 5:42 left to play. He followed with another jumper and an assist to Gary Trent on Minnesota's next two possessions. "It's nice to have somebody that size to be able to block shots, get the rebound, lead the break and then get the guy an assist," said Latrell Sprewell, another new member of the Timberwolves. "There's not a lot of players that can do that. He's probably the only guy that can do that in our league. It's nice to be beside him." Garnett, who shot 14-for-19, finished with eight points and seven rebounds in the fourth. "He was just phenomenal tonight," Wolves guard Fred Hoiberg said. "He was just in one of those zones where you just give him the ball and get out of the way." Cassell had 18 points and eight assists and Sprewell added 14 points for Minnesota. The banged-up Wolves, still missing Wally Szczerbiak (foot) and Troy Hudson (ankle), played without center Michael Olowokandi, who's nursing tendinitis in his right knee. But Minnesota got some key contributions from the bench to win its third straight game and send L.A. to its third consecutive loss. Hoiberg and Trent each scored 12 points. Trent, solid off the bench this season, hit a layup with 2:59 left to give the Wolves a 103-83 lead. "They hit big shots and some tough shots," Clippers coach Mike Dunleavy said. "But I think we also fell asleep a few times." Richardson was a one-man show for the Clippers, hitting from all over the floor. He scored his 36th point on a 21-foot jumper to pull the Clippers to 89-79 with 8:55 to go before the Wolves sealed it with a 14-4 run. Richardson's previous career high was 32 points on Nov. 11 against Atlanta. But the new mark didn't mean much to him. "I would rather take two points, zero points or whatever if we get a win," Richardson said. "I would sacrifice everything for a win." The Clippers went 0-3 on their road trip and face a rough week ahead with home games against Houston and New Jersey. "The guys have played hard on this trip," Dunleavy said. "We're just learning how to win. What we need to understand is, some possessions in a game mean more than others. We need to become smarter, better players." Minnesota led 34-19 after the first quarter, but the Clippers outscored the Wolves 14-4 to open the second and get back into it. Los Angeles cut the lead to 44-39 on Eddie House's 22-footer with 3:56 left in the half. But the Timberwolves closed out the half with a 10-2 run to take a 54-41 halftime lead. Garnett nearly had a double-double by halftime, scoring 16 points on 7-for-8 shooting and grabbing nine rebounds.

Game notes
C Mark Madsen started in place of Olowokandi. It wasn't immediately clear how many games Olowokandi, who's been limited in recent games, would miss. Saunders wouldn't comment on the injury. ... Sprewell made a nice assist late in the second quarter. After taking a long outlet pass, a guarded Sprewell wrapped the ball around his back to Hoiberg, who dunked to give Minnesota a 52-39 lead with 45.2 seconds left.
